items.name: Tatra 148 Truck (1972-1982) LoHA
items.description:
The Tatra 148 is a multipurpose truck that was developed in Czechoslovakia (now the Czech Republic and Slovakia) between 1969 and 1972. It was produced (1972-1982) by Tatra, a Czech vehicle manufacturer known for its off-road trucks. The Tatra 148 was designed as a versatile truck capable of handling all tasks and terrains. The truck was available in both 6x6 and 4x4 configurations, providing excellent off-road capabilities. It featured a V8 engine, which was a distinguishing characteristic of Tatra vehicles. The truck's adaptability allowed for the development of numerous (and some very unique) variants to suit different purposes and deployment in extreme conditions.

Rate the model, it helps with visibility on the site...

I am experimenting with LyCORIS/LoHA, various training settings, and training with or without tags (trying to get some reasonable training time while keeping target details and photorealism).

Trained 768x768, works well in high resolution and upscaling.

Use Hires. fix (4x_RealisticRescaler, 4x-Ultrasharp upscalers with denoising strength around 0.3-0.6) for best details! You can go quite creative with the model this way.

With Regional prompter and usual stable diffusion tricks, you can get really good and realistic (or stylized) scenes.

Experiment with weights around 0.7+, CLIP SKIP 1-2. The model works with a truck tatra148 token (it will propagate the style on other types of cars too).

For my notes on training and use of stable diffusion models, check https://sandner.art/articles/ai/

Support my work by buying me a coffee: https://ko-fi.com/airesearch

Have fun rendering!

items.name: Nothing Clay Mann
items.description:
CLIP SKIP = 1. Model was trained using CLIP SKIP 1.

I suggest using this VAE.

I wanted to get started on working on a model for myself, and this is the beginning of my new journey. This model was both trained and then merged.

The main objective of this model is to have a style that you can prompt for. If you don't prompt for it, the style is mostly a basic anime style.

If you prompt for "Clay Mann" (I suggest always using it as your first tag in the prompt to make it as strong as possible), it will use that style instead. So far, I'm very happy with the results and will probably keep iterating on this model.

Other than that, just use normal Booru-style prompting.

If you want to use a LoRA, it's a good idea to use the LoRA at low weights when also prompting for the Clay Mann style due to style conflict.

You can use tags like "outline," "lineart," "grayscale," "monochrome," "flat colors," "dark," and "vivid colors" in both positive and negative prompts, and they have a strong effect on the output. For example, if you want vivid colors, you can negate "grayscale" and "monochrome," and the output will end with brighter and stronger colors. I really like the outline and grayscale outputs from this model!

Nothingv2.3 as my base (cus its one of the best models I've ever used) + a private fine tuned model.

Model is heavily biased towards MY own taste.

Please check out my Ko-Fi page if you are interested in supporting me.

LoRA commissions open! -> Fiverr

items.name: Aaron - Hentai University
items.description:
This is a LoRA for the character Aaron, from Hentai University a game by Noodle Jacuzzi.

Aaron's art is from the artists Nagi Ichi and Silver Radish, the set -

Otokonoko to xx No. 1- Josou Shumi no Oshiego Hen~

I've been working my way through making these for all the characters currently in the game, and sharing them in the Discord for HU, but figured I should also put them up here.

In general, I'm working from pretty limited image sets, so expect the results to be a bit wonky at times. And this is one of the boys, so the usual AI wonkiness with feminine boys comes into play as well.

I recommend a weight of around 0.5, possibly lower depending if you're combining the character LoRA with other styles/costumes/etc. along with tagging some defining characteristics of the character you're generating. Higher than that can really push the artist's original style, and may cause you issues.

All characters I train have a "character tag" added into the set to help generate them fairly reliably.

Recommended LoRA Weight - 0.5 for fairly flexible, higher if you want more of the original artist's style, lower if it doesn't play nice with other loras.

Character tag - HUAaron, 1boy, flat chest,
Recommended tags -blue eyes, medium hair, brown hair,

I may have forgotten to check and tag eye color when doing my testing, but hey. If you want it to be "set accurate" be sure to tag.

I've got quite a backlog of these made up already, so I'll be uploading them on and off.

Check my other uploads as I put them out for more HU characters, and if you want any specific character put up soon, let me know.

items.name: Coffee Patina
items.description:
This model began as a failed physical art project. I created a 3D printed artwork using two filaments: the first containing powdered bronze, the second coloured with used coffee grounds. I treated the bronze components with vinegar to speed up the development of a patina. The contrast between the crystalline blues and greens of the patinaed bronze and the rich browns of the coffee was very pleasing, but the overall piece didn't come together as I had planned.

A few months later I took a close-up picture of the artwork and used this to train a LoRA that reproduces the varied textures and shades of the coffee and oxidised bronze. It can be tricky to find the right subjects and prompts for this model, but once these are found the rewards are rich colours, organic patterns, and a unique aesthetic.

items.name: T-X Endoskeleton
items.description:
Created for a user request. The 2000 version was trained for about 2000 steps, and the 4000 version was trained for about 4000 steps. The 2000 model is easier to pose and put into scenes, but has a hard time matching the T-X likeness consistently. The 4000 model will more reliably look like the T-X but is harder to place into scenes and will often appear solo, or turn other objects or people into a T-X.

Use the keyword txendo to activate. And make sure you also specify t-x endoskeleton in the prompt somewhere or it will sometimes look like a different robot. The model will add glowing blue lights and the hand weapon randomly, but you can increase the chance by using the blueglow keyword for the blue lights, and handwep for a hand that looks sort of like a plasma cannon (though it will sometimes just draw really really long fingers). Example prompts:
txendo, blueglow, a t-x endoskeleton standing in a dark room, intricate, highly detailed
txendo, handwep, blueglow, a t-x endoskeleton at a dance club, intricate, highly detailed

Please post your pics and leave a review. I love seeing what people make with the models I create.

Shout out to the first person who can guess what scene or video I'm describing in the tomato pictures (completely unrelated to Terminator). Leave a comment with your guess!

items.name: Acid Mix √Üsthetics : Holographic/Chrome/Glass Effects
items.description:
Acid Mix √Üsthetics

Here is a continuation of my work on acid-rave-brutalist-streetwear √¶sthetics.

Technically, it was trained with my Acid Poster lora as base.

I called it ACID MIX, and it ended vastly different from the first one, so i'm uploading separately rather than as version.

It is centered around these 5 main concepts :

  • "holo" : holographic. Works on clothes, body, cars, anything‚Ä¶ Very cool for abstract wallpaper. Possible to combine with keyword "swirl".

  • "glass" : see-through effect. Will maybe not work alone : try "holo glass".

  • "chrome " : create these strange chrome headgear. Also works on most things.

  • "glitch"

  • "neon"

Don't hesitate to mix these. Some other keywords include: "complementary colors", "flat" & "print" (will give a rough inked typed of image), "grid", "font" and "gothic font". You can still experiment with the keyword "poster", but it'll be less good than the Acid Poster Lora.

How to use

  • For abstract background, just keep weight:1

  • For faces and bodies : It produces ugly ass faces. That is why you will need to either lower the weight, between 0.1 to 0.7, recommended 0.5 OR else :

I very highly recommend that you download ADetailer extensions for better faces :

url instal : https://github.com/Bing-su/adetailer.

Copy any of the above pics generation data to get an idea of how it works. It's just an extra sampler. Example, if i want chrome effect, i can keep lora weight:1 in my prompt to retain full effect (if i want it), but the ADetailer will create a better face with light effect:

  • Under Detection, change Detection model confidence threshold to 0.1

  • Under Inpainting change Inpaint mask blur to 6 and Inpaint denoising strength from 0.5 to 0.6

  • ADetailer prompt: "chrome,¬†most stunning girl face <lora:acid mix:0.4> ",

  • ADetailer neg prompt: "(worst quality, low quality:1.3)"

The opposite is possible : to get a normal image with just chrome headgear, set very low acid mix weight in prompt, but a higher weight in ADetailer that will apply effect specifically on face.

On top of that i used ControlNet most of the time. With both of these your results will be much better.

CFG scale: tested at 3 (on EpicRealism), Clip skip: 2

Enjoy and please share your results !!

items.name: Cardology Mix
items.description:
Description

Sharing this because I've gotten a few requests for links. There are some similar models on the site already but it's fun to create your own "style", and to tweak this or that. I may upload multiple version. It's a semi-chibi mix with an artstyle anime and western animation, and it mixes decently with other LoRAs.

This series started with the recipe for AbyssHellMaple but has changed a lot since then. The name was because I was gonna use it for a card-based project at some point.

I really wanted a specific skin texture and I'm glad I could achieve it. It always reminded me of cookie dough for some reason.

Usage

Do whatever pretty much. You can reference the preview images for my usual settings. I recommend the VAE from AbyssOrangeMix3. It mixes pretty well with most character and style LoRAs. Backgrounds are pretty weak in v4 so you'll need to describe them more in your prompts.

Note: Civitai messes up parsing the negatives in the preview images due to an extension. Just remove the duplicate stuff from the regular prompt. ezpz

Components

I'm really annoyed when mixes don't share what goes into them. If you enjoy this model please give the authors some love. Basically I had a few different categories of models in mind when picking LoRAs to merge. v4 uses these

Base Model

  • AbyssOrangeMix3 (Use the VAE as well)

Chibi / Cute

  • Maplestory

  • PastelKa

  • Yaro

  • Yuzusoft Chibi

Squishable Faces

  • aaaa

  • Yudeebi

General Style

  • Helltaker

  • Takamichi

  • Pixar

Each have a mix weight of between 0.1 and 0.4. I found adding a 3d render based lora (pixar in v4) really cleans things up.

Suggestions for use:

If the face appears to be falling apart, and you want to improve the quality of the face, use Inpaint and Inpaint area use !!only Masked!! (Best results) to get a better face, or use Hires. fix to improve, use other seed or tools is also a good way.

Higher resolution (a little higher than 512 * 512) plus Hires. fix, picture quality will be better (if the gpu memory is not enough you can try a Low magnification of Hires. fix or other upscale tools).

Positive prompt for image quality (like best quality) are unnecessary and reduce the possibilities of the picture, also make the picture tend to be in a style.

It's better to Use the weight you would have used for positive quality prompt on negative quality prompt.

If you feel that the content of the picture is not rich enough, You can try to describe in detail to make the picture more closely to your imagination.

The weight of the prompt word and the order in which it is used affects how important it is in the picture.

If there are prompt words that you cannot respond to, please rank the problems in the following order: synonyms (different descriptions of the same concept), prompt word conflicts (positive and negative), model problems (see if other models can respond to the same prompt words), embedding (I am not in the habit of using it, but considering its rationale, I put it up as a reference).

If you want to sweepstakes with few prompts, it is better to add umbrella to the negative prompt (at least in V1).

I usually use clip2 when the results don't meet expectations.

Use lora as you like!

items.name: Letho | The Witcher 2: Assassins of Kings
items.description:
Character Lora of Letho of Gulet from The Witcher 3 : Wild Hunt/ The Witcher 2: Assassins of Kings

"Goddamn fools." -Letho

Steroids ? All natural, said letho and I believed him -soul3142


This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives 4.0 International License.

My Witcher LoRA Index - soul3142's Guide to the Witcher Universe.

If you want to, you can support me on Patreon or Buy me Coffee.

Main Trigger Word - letho_soul3142 , check examples for other ones.

Recommendations :-

  1. Highres Fix - must, if you are getting blurry and ugly images

    My upscale method: txt2img 512x768 -> send to img2img -> controlnet tile upscale, tile diffusion 2x scale with 4xUltrasharp upscaler and tiled vae

  2. Weight: 0.7 - 0.8

  3. Clip Skip: 2

  4. Steps: 25-30

  5. CFG: 7-8

  6. Denoising - Don't go too high, it can alter a lot of details

I use 0.7 weight, 25 steps, Euler a, Clip skip 2 in nearly all my examples with almost same, simple +ve/-ve prompts regardless of checkpoint for my own consistency purposes.

There are imperfections here & there, which i usually leave it in as is, (i never do any inpainting in examples), most of which like hands can be fixed with better prompting, negative embeddings while other like weapons are just bad majority of the time no matter the model as of today.

Some LoRA's are flexible with any clothing, some are not (usually character's with single costume) so keep these things in mind.

This is an unofficial fanmade LoRA, not intended for any commercial purpose and use. All characters and IP rights are owned by their respective creators and owners. I do not own rights to any of these characters.

The quokka (/Ààkw…ík…ô/) (Setonix brachyurus)is a small macropod about the size of a domestic cat. It is the only member of the genus Setonix. Like other marsupials in the macropod family (such as kangaroos and wallabies), the quokka is herbivorous and mainly nocturnal.

Quokkas are found on some smaller islands off the coast of Western Australia, particularly Rottnest Island just off Perth and Bald Island near Albany. Isolated, scattered populations also exist in forest and coastal heath between Perth and Albany. A small colony inhabits a protected area of Two Peoples Bay Nature Reserve, where they co-exist with the critically endangered Gilbert's potoroo.
